@page "/"

<PageTitle>Home</PageTitle>

<section class="hero-panel">
    <span class="eyebrow">Week 7 Project 06</span>
    <h1>Introduce Blazor with a simple shared counter.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        This project uses Blazor Server interactive components so button clicks run C# methods and the counter value updates in connected browsers automatically.
    </p>
    <div class="action-row">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/counter">Open The Counter Demo</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="card-grid">
    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>What students practise</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Create a basic Razor component.</li>
            <li>Handle button clicks with C# methods.</li>
            <li>Update UI state without writing JavaScript.</li>
            <li>Observe how Blazor Server keeps connected clients in sync.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>Why this sample is useful</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>The component is intentionally small and readable.</li>
            <li>The shared service makes the real-time behavior easy to see.</li>
            <li>Students can compare this approach with the earlier Fetch API and HTMX projects.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>
</section>

<section class="info-panel">
    <h2>Suggested walkthrough</h2>
    <ol>
        <li>Open the counter page in two browser tabs.</li>
        <li>Click increment in one tab and observe the value change in both tabs.</li>
        <li>Click decrement and reset to see C# event handling update the UI again.</li>
    </ol>
</section>
